</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC10FF86F181AE923538F8E1" blockId="108.[189,1399,961,1833]" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">
Fore wing length 
<quantity id="ED21F28DFC10FF86F0A7AE923674FC14" box="[411,548,962,988]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" unit="mm" value="15.0" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="14.0">14–16 mm</quantity>
. Antenna with 53–62 flagellomeres. First flagellomere about 3.0–3.5 times as long as wide. Central flagellomeres in male usually longer than in 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC10FF86F548AEB53171FC37" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[1140,1313,997,1023]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuratus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC10FF86F548AEB53171FC37" box="[1140,1313,997,1023]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. obscuratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, about 1.6 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC10FF86F337A958363FFBEA" box="[523,623,1032,1058]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1746,1772]" captionTargetBox="[371,1220,293,1682]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[340,1247,262,1708]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 7. A–D. Occipital carina posterior view. A. Ophion confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). B. O. mocsaryi Brauns, 1889. C. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. D. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. E–G. Hind trochanter and trochantellus dorsal view. E. O. slaviceki Kriechbaumer, 1892. F. O. obscuratus Fabricius, 1798. G. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. H–I. Mandible ventral view. H. O. obscuratus. I. O. slaviceki. J–K. First tergite, aberration O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. J. Dorsal view. K. Lateral view. L–M. Head in posterior view showing generalized shape of occipital carina. L. O. obscuratus. M. O. variegatus Rudow, 1883. N–O. Central flagellomeres in males. N. O. obscuratus. O. O. variegatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476416/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 7O</figureCitation>
). Subapical flagellomeres approximately 1.5–1.6 times as long as wide. Temples slightly buccate. Head in lateral view temple 0.7–0.8 times as long as compound eye in females and 0.5–0.6 times in males. Face wide in anterior view (
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC10FF86F574A91E30ECFBA1" box="[1096,1212,1102,1129]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="28.[189,232,1881,1907]" captionTargetBox="[270,1318,265,1837]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[270,1318,265,1837]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Fig. 17. Head, anterior view. A. Ophion variegatus Rudow, 1883, female. B. O. sylvestris Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008721). C. O. perkinsi Brock, 1982, ♂. D. O. norei Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♂ (NHRS-HEVA000008687). E. O. perkinsi, ♀. F. O. norei Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008691)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476442" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476442/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 17A</figureCitation>
). Gap between compound eye and lateral ocellus usually distinct, about 0.3 times the diameter of ocellus. Occipital carina usually curved before junction with hypostomal carina, junction usually with an angle of 70–90 degrees (
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC10FF86F0BCA9E835BCFB1B" box="[384,492,1208,1235]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1746,1772]" captionTargetBox="[371,1220,293,1682]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[340,1247,262,1708]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 7. A–D. Occipital carina posterior view. A. Ophion confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). B. O. mocsaryi Brauns, 1889. C. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. D. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. E–G. Hind trochanter and trochantellus dorsal view. E. O. slaviceki Kriechbaumer, 1892. F. O. obscuratus Fabricius, 1798. G. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. H–I. Mandible ventral view. H. O. obscuratus. I. O. slaviceki. J–K. First tergite, aberration O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. J. Dorsal view. K. Lateral view. L–M. Head in posterior view showing generalized shape of occipital carina. L. O. obscuratus. M. O. variegatus Rudow, 1883. N–O. Central flagellomeres in males. N. O. obscuratus. O. O. variegatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476416/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Figs 7M</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC10FF86F0C6A9E83662FB1B" box="[506,562,1208,1235]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="123.[189,232,1947,1973]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,680,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@123.[189,1399,679,1905]" captionTargetPageId="123" captionText="Fig. 50. Ophion variegatus Rudow, 1883, neotype, ♀ (MNHN). A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Epicnemial carina, lateroventral view. C. Occipital carina, lateroventral view. D. Labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476516" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476516/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">50C</figureCitation>
). Malar space about 0.2 times as long as mandibular base in female and male. Mandibular gape right-angled, with internal angles. Wing membrane clear. Ramellus usually short, reaching 0.1–0.3 times the width of the discosubmarginal cell. Radius sinuous. Structure of mesopleuron shining or with distinct microsculptures between punctures, with weak, very regular punctation consisting of small punctures. Interstices between punctures about equal to their diameter, up to 2.0 times their diameter. Epicnemial carina, in antero-ventral view, with pleurosternal angles obviously anterior to sternal angles. Pleurosternal angles rounded, usually right angled, rarely obtuse or slightly acute. Sternal angles usually more distinct and the epicnemal carina between the sternal and pleurosternal angles more concave than in 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC10FF86F2D7A88230C5FA24" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[1003,1173,1490,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuratus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC10FF86F2D7A88230C5FA24" box="[1003,1173,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. obscuratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC10FF86F59AA8823143FA24" box="[1190,1299,1489,1516]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="123.[189,232,1947,1973]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,680,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@123.[189,1399,679,1905]" captionTargetPageId="123" captionText="Fig. 50. Ophion variegatus Rudow, 1883, neotype, ♀ (MNHN). A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Epicnemial carina, lateroventral view. C. Occipital carina, lateroventral view. D. Labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476516" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476516/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 50B</figureCitation>
) but the overlap is considerable. Scutellum without lateral carinae. Structure of propodeum similar to that of 
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC10FF86F181AB493564F9FA" box="[189,308,1560,1587]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC10FF86F181AB493561F9FA" authorityName="Johansson &amp; Cederberg" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[189,305,1560,1587]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteus">O. luteus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Posterior to anterior transverse carina mostly shining. Anterior transverse carina always present centrally anterior to area superomedia, but often also present laterally, though rarely strongly raised. Posterior transverse carina usually only present laterally, widely interrupted centrally (as in 
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC10FF86F181ABD2357DF954" box="[189,301,1666,1692]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1739,1765]" captionTargetBox="[305,1281,298,1666]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[263,1325,265,1697]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 10. Generalized carination of propodeum in females, posterodorsal view. A. Ophion luteus (Linnaeus, 1758)/O. scutellaris Thomson, 1888/O. obscuratus Fabricius, 1792. B. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. C. O. brocki Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008633). D. O. confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). E. O. crassicornis Brock, 1982. F. O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. G. O. ellenae Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008655). H. O. perkinsi Brock, 1982. I. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. J. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. K. O. dispar Brauns, 1895. L. O. tenuicornis Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008743). M. O. longigena Thomson, 1888. N. O. brevicornis Morley, 1915. O. O. forticornis Morley, 1915." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476424/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
). Central longitudinal carinae weak or absent. Sclerotised part of first sternite ending level to spiracle. Legs normal with hind femur about 6.0–7.0 times as long as wide. Hind trochantellus usually longer than in other species except 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC10FF86F3F5AB993767F92A" authorityName="Johansson &amp; Cederberg" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[713,823,1736,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC10FF86F3F5AB993767F92A" box="[713,823,1736,1763]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. luteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC10FF86F27AAB993786F92A" authorityName="Kriechbaumer" authorityYear="1892" box="[838,982,1736,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="slaviceki">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC10FF86F27AAB993786F92A" box="[838,982,1736,1763]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. slaviceki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC10FF86F52DAB9930EBF92A" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[1041,1211,1736,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuratus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC10FF86F52DAB9930EBF92A" box="[1041,1211,1736,1763]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. obscuratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as in 
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC10FF86F431AB983136F92B" box="[1293,1382,1736,1763]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1746,1772]" captionTargetBox="[371,1220,293,1682]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[340,1247,262,1708]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 7. A–D. Occipital carina posterior view. A. Ophion confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). B. O. mocsaryi Brauns, 1889. C. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. D. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. E–G. Hind trochanter and trochantellus dorsal view. E. O. slaviceki Kriechbaumer, 1892. F. O. obscuratus Fabricius, 1798. G. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. H–I. Mandible ventral view. H. O. obscuratus. I. O. slaviceki. J–K. First tergite, aberration O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. J. Dorsal view. K. Lateral view. L–M. Head in posterior view showing generalized shape of occipital carina. L. O. obscuratus. M. O. variegatus Rudow, 1883. N–O. Central flagellomeres in males. N. O. obscuratus. O. O. variegatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476416/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 7F</figureCitation>
). Slightly shorter than wide in dorsal view. Inner spur of hind tibia long about 0.3–0.4 times as long as metatarsus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC10FF86F181AA003544F8A2" blockId="108.[189,276,1872,1898]" box="[189,276,1872,1898]" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">
<heading id="712EE804FC10FF86F181AA003544F8A2" bold="true" box="[189,276,1872,1898]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" reason="3">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC10FF86F181AA003544F8A2" bold="true" box="[189,276,1872,1898]" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Colour</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC10FF86F181AA2E30E1F874" blockId="108.[189,1399,1918,1980]" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">
Body usually more brownish than other species and with extensive whitish pattern on thorax (
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC10FF86F5E2AA2E317DF851" box="[1246,1325,1918,1945]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="19.[189,232,1948,1974]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,780,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[189,1398,780,1904]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Fig. 11. Head and mesosoma, lateral and dorsal view of female. A‒B. Ophion variegatus Rudow, 1883. C‒D. O. ventricosus Gravenhorst, 1829." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476428" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476428/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
A–B), similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC10FF86F0BBAAF2367CF874" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[391,556,1954,1980]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuratus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC10FF86F0BBAAF2367CF874" box="[391,556,1954,1980]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. obscuratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Mandibular teeth black. Ovipositor sheath testaceous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC11FF87F181AC5B3536FEED" blockId="109.[189,358,267,293]" box="[189,358,267,293]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">
<heading id="712EE804FC11FF87F181AC5B3536FEED" bold="true" box="[189,358,267,293]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" reason="3">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC11FF87F181AC5B3536FEED" bold="true" box="[189,358,267,293]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">DNA barcode</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC11FF87F181AC693565FE53" blockId="109.[189,1399,313,411]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">
The DNA barcode sequences of 15 Swedish specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC11FF87F258AC69306FFE9B" authorityName="Johansson &amp; Cederberg" authorityYear="2019" box="[868,1087,313,339]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegatus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC11FF87F258AC69306FFE9B" box="[868,1087,313,339]" italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Ophion variegatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are available at the BOLD systems database (www.boldsystems.org, Specimen codes: STI-NJBC: 99, 101–103, 199–206, 210, 312, 316).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62C30CE3FC11FF87F181AC9137C1FDBB" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC11FF87F181AC913570FE13" blockId="109.[189,288,449,475]" box="[189,288,449,475]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">
<heading id="712EE804FC11FF87F181AC913570FE13" bold="true" box="[189,288,449,475]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" reason="3">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC11FF87F181AC913570FE13" bold="true" box="[189,288,449,475]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Ecology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC11FF87F181ACA037C1FDBB" blockId="109.[189,1399,496,628]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC11FF87F181ACA035CAFDC2" authorityName="Johansson &amp; Cederberg" authorityYear="2019" box="[189,410,496,522]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegatus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC11FF87F181ACA035CAFDC2" box="[189,410,496,522]" italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Ophion variegatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in a variety of different habitats ranging from semi-open forests to gardens and hedgerows. Host records from 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC11FF87F352AF4330E4FDE5" authority="(Hubner, 1808) (Brock 1982)" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1808" baseAuthorityName="Hubner" baseAuthorityYear="1808" box="[622,1204,531,557]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Mythimna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="impura">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC11FF87F352AF433715FDE5" box="[622,837,531,557]" italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Mythimna impura</emphasis>
(Hübner, 1808) (
<bibRefCitation id="4E482299FC11FF87F527AF4330FCFDE5" author="Brock" box="[1051,1196,531,557]" firstAuthor="Brock" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" pagination="57 - 97" refId="ref63572" refString="Brock J. P. 1982. A systematic study of the genus Ophion in Britain (Hymenoptera, Ichneumonidae). Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 125: 57 - 97." type="journal article" year="1982">Brock 1982</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
probably refers to this species. 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC11FF87F04BAF663604FD98" authorityName="Johansson &amp; Cederberg" authorityYear="2019" box="[375,596,566,592]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegatus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC11FF87F04BAF663604FD98" box="[375,596,566,592]" italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Ophion variegatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is active from May to June in Southern 
<collectingCountry id="52CE1FF8FC11FF87F503AF6630CCFD98" box="[1087,1180,566,592]" name="Sweden" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Sweden</collectingCountry>
and flies until the beginning of August in the Northern parts of Central 
<collectingCountry id="52CE1FF8FC11FF87F210AF0937DDFDBB" box="[812,909,601,627]" name="Sweden" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Sweden</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62C30CE3FC11FF87F181AFCB364BFD2B" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC11FF87F181AFCB358DFD7D" blockId="109.[189,477,667,693]" box="[189,477,667,693]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">
<heading id="712EE804FC11FF87F181AFCB358DFD7D" bold="true" box="[189,477,667,693]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" reason="3">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC11FF87F181AFCB358DFD7D" bold="true" box="[189,477,667,693]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">
Distribution in 
<collectingCountry id="52CE1FF8FC11FF87F041AFCB358DFD7D" box="[381,477,667,693]" name="Sweden" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Sweden</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC11FF87F181AF99364BFD2B" blockId="109.[189,539,713,739]" box="[189,539,713,739]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">
Southern and Central 
<collectingCountry id="52CE1FF8FC11FF87F082AF99364BFD2B" box="[446,539,713,739]" name="Sweden" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Sweden</collectingCountry>
</paragraph>
